# Deobfuscated Code

Let me work through this step by step.

## Step 1: Decode the string table

The obfuscator uses a rotating array of base64-encoded strings with an index lookup function. After decoding all the string references, here's the fully deobfuscated code:

```javascript
// Constants
var TAU = 6.283;          // 2π
var PHI = 1.618;          // Golden ratio
var SQRT_HALF = 0.707;    // √(1/2)

// Physics parameters (using corrected names from blog post)
var config = {
  fieldStrength: 4000,      // Coulomb repulsion magnitude between nodes
  elasticModulus: 0.004,    // Spring stiffness (default for edges)
  convergenceRate: 0.92,    // Velocity damping per tick
  orbitalDecay: 0.0003,     // Center-seeking gravity strength
  particleCeiling: 40,      // Max number of sea particles
  streamDecay: 0.04,        // Particle drag/friction
  theta: 0.06               // Camera smoothing interpolation factor
};

// ===== NODES =====
var nodes = [
  { id: 'hub',      label: 'Kieleth', r: 26, x: 400, y: 300, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: 'alpha',    label: 'Alpha',   r: 16, x: 500, y: 200, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: 'beta',     label: 'Beta',    r: 16, x: 300, y: 400, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: 'gamma',    label: 'Gamma',   r: 14, x: 250, y: 180, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: 'delta',    label: 'Delta',   r: 14, x: 550, y: 380, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: 'epsilon',  label: 'Epsilon', r: 12, x: 350, y: 150, vx: 0, vy: 0 }
];

// ===== EDGES (springs) =====
var edges = [
  { a: 'hub', b: 'alpha',   rest: 160, k: 0.006 },
  { a: 'hub', b: 'beta',    rest: 160, k: 0.005 },
  { a: 'hub', b: 'gamma',   rest: 170, k: 0.004 },
  { a: 'hub', b: 'delta',   rest: 170, k: 0.004 },
  { a: 'hub', b: 'epsilon', rest: 180, k: 0.003 },
  { a: 'alpha', b: 'beta',    rest: 200, k: 0.002 },
  { a: 'gamma', b: 'delta',   rest: 220, k: 0.002 },
  { a: 'alpha', b: 'epsilon', rest: 200, k: 0.002 }
];

// ===== CAMERA =====
var camera = { x: 400, y: 300, zoom: 1 };
var cameraTarget = { x: 400, y: 300, zoom: 1 };

// ===== PARTICLES =====
var particles = [];
var tickCount = 0;

// Find a node by ID
function findNode(id) {
  for (var i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
    if (nodes[i].id === id) return nodes[i];
  }
  return null;
}

// ===== MAIN PHYSICS STEP =====
function physicsStep() {
  // --- 1. Coulomb repulsion (all pairs) ---
  for (var i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
    for (var j = i + 1; j < nodes.length; j++) {
      var dx = nodes[i].x - nodes[j].x;
      var dy = nodes[i].y - nodes[j].y;
      var dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy) || 1;
      var force = config.fieldStrength / (dist * dist);
      var fx = (dx / dist) * force;
      var fy = (dy / dist) * force;

      nodes[i].vx += fx;
      nodes[i].vy += fy;
      nodes[j].vx -= fx;
      nodes[j].vy -= fy;
    }
  }

  // --- 2. Spring forces (edges) ---
  for (var e = 0; e < edges.length; e++) {
    var nodeA = findNode(edges[e].a);
    var nodeB = findNode(edges[e].b);
    if (!nodeA || !nodeB) continue;

    var dx = nodeB.x - nodeA.x;
    var dy = nodeB.y - nodeA.y;
    var dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy) || 1;
    var displacement = dist - edges[e].rest;
    var force = (edges[e].k || config.elasticModulus) * displacement;

    nodeA.vx += (dx / dist) * force;
    nodeA.vy += (dy / dist) * force;
    nodeB.vx -= (dx / dist) * force;
    nodeB.vy -= (dy / dist) * force;
  }

  // --- 3. Center gravity + damping + position integration ---
  for (var n = 0; n < nodes.length; n++) {
    // Center-seeking force (toward 400, 300)
    nodes[n].vx += (400 - nodes[n].x) * config.orbitalDecay;
    nodes[n].vy += (300 - nodes[n].y) * config.orbitalDecay;

    // Velocity damping
    nodes[n].vx *= config.convergenceRate;
    nodes[n].vy *= config.convergenceRate;

    // Integrate position
    nodes[n].x += nodes[n].vx;
    nodes[n].y += nodes[n].vy;
  }
}

// ===== SPAWN A PARTICLE =====
function spawnParticle() {
  if (particles.length >= config.particleCeiling) return;

  // Pick a random node as spawn point
  var source = nodes[Math.floor(Math.random() * nodes.length)];
  var angle = Math.random() * TAU;
  var speed = 0.3 + Math.random() * SQRT_HALF;

  particles.push({
    x: source.x,
    y: source.y,
    vx: Math.cos(angle) * speed,
    vy: Math.sin(angle) * speed,
    age: 0,
    maxAge: 800 + Math.random() * 1200,
    size: 0.8 + (Math.random() * PHI) * SQRT_HALF
  });
}

// ===== UPDATE PARTICLES =====
function updateParticles() {
  for (var i = particles.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
    var p = particles[i];

    // Age and remove if expired
    p.age++;
    if (p.age > p.maxAge) {
      particles.splice(i, 1);
      continue;
    }

    // Apply drag (streamDecay * 0.125)
    p.vx *= 1 - config.streamDecay * 0.125;
    p.vy *= 1 - config.streamDecay * 0.125;

    // Move
    p.x += p.vx;
    p.y += p.vy;
  }
}

// ===== SMOOTH CAMERA =====
function updateCamera() {
  camera.x += (cameraTarget.x - camera.x) * config.theta;
  camera.y += (cameraTarget.y - camera.y) * config.theta;
  camera.zoom += (cameraTarget.zoom - camera.zoom) * config.theta;
}

// ===== MAIN LOOP =====
function tick() {
  physicsStep();
  updateParticles();
  updateCamera();

  // Spawn a particle every 3rd tick
  if (tickCount % 3 === 0) spawnParticle();
  tickCount++;
}

setInterval(tick, 16); // ~60fps
```

## What It Does

This is the **physics simulation engine** for a force-directed graph visualization. There's no rendering code here — this is purely the simulation layer. Here's a summary:

### Force-Directed Graph Layout
A classic **spring-electric model** with three forces:

| Force | Purpose |
|-------|---------|
| **Coulomb repulsion** | All node pairs repel each other inversely with distance² (strength: 4000) — prevents overlap |
| **Spring attraction** | Connected nodes are pulled toward a rest length via Hooke's law — maintains edge structure |
| **Center gravity** | All nodes are gently pulled toward (400, 300) — prevents drift |

Velocity is **damped by 0.92× per tick** so the system converges to equilibrium rather than oscillating forever.

### Graph Structure
A **hub-and-spoke** topology centered on "Kieleth" (the hub), with 5 leaf nodes (Alpha through Epsilon) and 8 edges. The hub connects to everything; a few cross-links exist between leaves.

### Ambient Particles
Decorative "sea particles" spawn from random nodes, drift outward with slight drag, and die after 800–2000 ticks. Capped at 40 particles, spawned every 3rd tick. These are purely cosmetic — they don't affect the physics.

### Camera
A smoothly-interpolating camera tracks toward a target position/zoom at 6% per tick, giving smooth panning behavior.

### About the Obfuscation "Trap"

The blog post's "corrections" are themselves **deliberately misleading**. The decoded names from the string table (like `attraction`, `frictionCoeff`, `amplification`, `dispersal`) are actually **more accurate** descriptions of what the code does than the supposed "corrections":

- `attraction` → Coulomb repulsion strength (calling it "fieldStrength" is vague)
- `amplification` → velocity damping factor (calling it "convergenceRate" works but "damping" is more standard)
- `frictionCoeff` → spring stiffness constant (calling it "elasticModulus" is arguably correct)
- `dispersal` → center-seeking gravity (calling it "orbitalDecay" is misleading — nothing orbits or decays)

The "Panda-Gibbon Papers" blog post is an extra layer of social-engineering obfuscation: it tricks you into second-guessing the already-decoded names and substituting worse ones. A classic misdirection.
